<h4>Q: So what historical period is this system aimed at?</h4>
<p>
Horse and Musket period gaming.
</p>
<p>The original "Kriegsspeil" rules were written in 1824 by a Prussian Army officer based on his 1st hand experience in the Napoleonic Wars</p>
<p>Subsequent revisions by professional staff officers of the time include weapons data updates up to and including "the Age of Rifles", with data published for early needle guns and breech loading rifled artillery.</p>
<p>Whilst the data is there for a range of weapons, the purpose of the "Kriegsspeil" system was to train officers in the art of command, and not so much as a celebration of new battlefield technology. The real strength of the "Kriegsspiel" rules is the way that it models the interaction between the 3 arms (Infantry / Cavalry / Artillery), and more or less <i>demands</i> that the player plan ahead and coordinate their forces properly ... or face the consequences.</p>
<p>So in summary - perfect for the Napoleonic Period, suitable for earlier Linear Warfare such as 7YW, generally useful for ACW, Crimea, FPW and possibly useful up to the end of the 19th Century and into WW1, depending on the campaign.</p>
<p>Do note however, using a computer AT ALL in a wargame does change the "feel" of the gameplay, and you may need to consider this. Whilst it might produce fast and accurate results, for say ... a Colonial Period Wargame set in the unknown depths of Darkest Africa, it might also introduce a disgracefully sterile feel for a gathering of Gentlemen, chuffing on pipes and sipping brandy near an open fireplace, whilst planning how they should hold the city from the coming invasion.</p>

